{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598201"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.14,0.26,0.17,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116602"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46438"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116602"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to her GP with a three-month history of bloody diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and weight loss. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with normal vital signs. Colonoscopy reveals continuous inflammation extending from the rectum to the descending colon. Multiple biopsies are taken.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopic examination shows architectural distortion of the crypts with branching and shortening. There is a marked increase in inflammatory cells within the lamina propria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely predominant inflammatory cell type in the lamina propria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eosinophils","Mast cells","Neutrophils","Plasma cells","Macrophages"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of ulcerative colitis, showing characteristic histological changes including architectural distortion and increased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. The predominant cell types in chronic inflammatory bowel disease are \u003Cstrong\u003Eplasma cells\u003C/strong\u003E and lymphocytes, reflecting the chronic nature of the inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in acute inflammation and their presence in the crypts (cryptitis) or crypt abscesses indicates active disease. However, they are not the predominant cell type in the lamina propria in chronic inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophils\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in inflammatory bowel disease but are not typically the predominant cell type. A marked increase in eosinophils would be more suggestive of allergic conditions or parasitic infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMast cells\u003C/strong\u003E play a role in inflammatory bowel disease through release of inflammatory mediators, but they are not the predominant cell type seen on histological examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrophages\u003C/strong\u003E are present in inflammatory bowel disease and contribute to the inflammatory process, but they are not as numerous as plasma cells in the lamina propria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of plasma cells in the lamina propria reflects the chronic nature of the inflammation and the ongoing immune response. These cells produce antibodies and are a key feature of the adaptive immune response in inflammatory bowel disease. The degree of plasma cell infiltration often correlates with disease severity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammatory bowel disease shows increased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria, particularly plasma cells and lymphocytes.","The presence of neutrophils suggests active disease in inflammatory bowel disease.","Architectural distortion of crypts is a key feature of chronic inflammatory bowel disease."],"references":["Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T05:32:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T05:33:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116602"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/